<subSubSection id="C34A6531FFBFFF84FF4DC8D28E66FCD8" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BEF36BAFFBFFF84FF4DC8D28E66FCD8" blockId="7.[135,774,733,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FF4DC8D28E1FFD38" bold="true" box="[135,271,733,757]" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FE1FC8D28D08FD38" box="[469,536,733,757]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">aliger</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFBFFF84FDE7C8D28D6EFD38" box="[557,638,733,757]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Malihkaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aligera">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FDE7C8D28D6EFD38" box="[557,638,733,757]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">aligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FD5AC8D28DE5FD38" box="[656,757,733,757]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">aligerum</emphasis>
), winged. An adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34A6531FFBFFF8BFF4DC9328DF5FE99" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEF36BAFFBFFF8BFF4DC9328DF5FE99" blockId="7.[135,774,829,885]" lastBlockId="8.[113,755,188,341]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FF4DC9328FE6FC98" bold="true" box="[135,246,829,853]" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">Remarks.</emphasis>
The colour pattern of the six available specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFBFFF84FF6DC9518E0BFCB8" box="[167,283,861,885]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Malihkaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aligera">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FF6DC9518E0BFCB8" box="[167,283,861,885]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">M. aligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is made of very regular bars on body, with very well marked edges, on a pale background. This general pattern is rare among Southeast Asian nemacheilids. Interestingly, one of the species collected together with 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFBFFF84FA6DC9038C80FC8E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Malihkaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aligera">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FA6DC9038C80FC8E" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">M. aligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFBFFF84FC61C9248B9EFC8E" box="[939,1166,811,835]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Schistura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sikmaiensis">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FC61C9248B9EFC8E" box="[939,1166,811,835]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">Schistura sikmaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which also has a regular and contrasted colour pattern (
<figureCitation id="136B2A3FFFBFFF84FB94C9448BB1FCAE" box="[1118,1185,843,867]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[136,171,2093,2115]" captionTargetBox="[274,1336,951,2077]" captionTargetId="figure-200@7.[274,1336,951,2077]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 7. Schistura sikmaiensis, CMK 25560; Myanmar: Irrawaddy drainage: Mula River at Lika; a, female, 61.6 mm SL; b, male, 72.7 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4504513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4504513/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). A third species collected at the same locality is 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFBFFF84FBFAC9638BBDFC4E" authorityName="Kottelat" authorityYear="2017" box="[1072,1197,875,899]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Schistura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nubigena">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFBFFF84FBFAC9638BBDFC4E" box="[1072,1197,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="87">S. nubigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(described below), which has a sharply contrasted colour pattern of 4 bold black bars on a whitish background. Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D39FFB0FF8BFDCBCAD28DA1FF39" authorityName="Kottelat" authorityYear="2017" box="[513,689,220,244]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemacheilidae" genus="Schistura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="88" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wanlainensis">
<emphasis id="B924EAA8FFB0FF8BFDCBCAD28DA1FF39" box="[513,689,220,244]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="88">S. wanlainensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also described below, from the same area but at higher altitude and habitat with higher gradient, also has a very contrasted colour pattern of very regular bars on a pale background.
